ce:section.ce:para:
The AFM images show that the Mg(OH)2 sheets are ca. 2 nm thick (Fig. S1) and are heavily aggregated. The XRD pattern shows it is hexagonal magnesium hydroxide phase (JCPDF044-1482). TEM analyses of AgEG/Mg(OH)2, AgHT/Mg(OH)2 and AgPR/Mg(OH)2 confirm that they all consist of AgNPs of similar size distributions ranging 3–120 nm (
                        Fig. 1A; 
                        Table 1). In the diffuse-reflectance UV–vis spectra, the peaks at ca. 400 nm are attributed to surface plasmon resonance (SPR) of AgNPs (Fig. 1B) and meanwhile the strong absorbance of AgPR/Mg(OH)2 at λ > 500 nm may be caused by aggregation of AgNPs [44]. Hence, the absorption properties of the three materials in the visible light region are similar. Elemental analyses show that the contents of Ag(0), AgCl and Mg(OH)2 of AgEG/Mg(OH)2 are also similar to those of AgHT/Mg(OH)2 and AgPR/Mg(OH)2. Meanwhile, FT-IR spectra indicate that no organic residue remains on the surfaces of the materials (Fig. S2). In addition, the BET area values of the three materials are close to each other.
